## Phase 5: Windows UX Guidelines Checklist

Read each changed form's Designer.cs and apply these checks:

**Naming & Labels:**
- Control labels use sentence case ("Start homing" not "Start Homing" or "START HOMING")
- Units are shown in labels (e.g., "Speed (mm/s):" not just "Speed:")
- Error messages are specific — say what's wrong and what to do

**Visual Grouping:**
- Related controls are in GroupBox or Panel containers
- GroupBox titles are short (≤20 chars) and descriptive
- Dangerous operations (emergency stop, valve open) are visually separated from routine controls

**Status & Feedback:**
- Status changes (device connected/disconnected) are shown in StatusStrip, not pop-up dialogs
- Long operations show progress (ProgressBar or animated indicator) — no frozen UI
- Confirmation dialogs exist for irreversible operations (not just destructive ones)

**Device Control Specific:**
- Numeric input fields for device parameters have valid range shown (e.g., min/max in label or tooltip)
- Move/activate buttons are disabled when device is not ready
- Emergency stop button is visually prominent and always enabled

